Notable risks / red flags
1. Firmware write protection concern
The firmware contains this configuration string:
{"WriteProtectionEnabled": "No"}
That is a concern. It does not prove the live hardware is currently unlocked, because runtime hardware registers and manufacturing-state locks must be checked on the actual machine. But it is enough to treat this image cautiously.
2. 
Fpt.efi
can flash firmware
The UEFI executable can write SPI flash regions. If a malicious actor supplied this package, the attack path would be simple: boot EFI shell, run FPT, flash 1.bin, and persist below the OS.
3. Unsigned EFI executable
Fpt.efi has no embedded Authenticode certificate table. If Secure Boot is properly enforced, an unsigned EFI app normally should not run unless it is enrolled/allowed another way. If it runs freely, that suggests Secure Boot is off, bypassed, or not enforcing this binary.
4. Cannot prove Secure Boot / Boot Guard state from the dump alone
I found SecureBootSetup and BootGuardPei, but that only shows firmware support/components. It does not prove Secure Boot or Intel Boot Guard Verified Boot are enabled on the target hardware.
5. Board-specific data risk
Flashing a full SPI image can overwrite SMBIOS, serial numbers, MAC addresses, PDR/customer data, NVRAM variables, and OEM provisioning. Intel community guidance notes SMBIOS data can be lost during firmware upgrades and recommends using PDR for customer-specific data.  
